{"title_page": "Yegor Gaidar", "text_new": "{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|\u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440, \u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Timurovich|Gaidar}}\n\n{{Infobox prime minister\n|birth_name=Yegor Timurovich Gaidar\n|name = Yegor Gaidar<br />{{small|\u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440}}\n|image = Gaidar in 2008 - crop.jpg\n|imagesize = 240px\n|caption = Gaidar in 2008\n|office = [[Prime Minister of Russia]]<br>{{small|Acting}}\n|term_start = 15 June 1992\n|term_end = 15 December 1992\n|1blankname = [[First Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation|First Deputy]]\n|1namedata = [[Vladimir Shumeyko]]\n|president = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|predecessor = [[Boris Yeltsin]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|successor = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n|order2 = [[First Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation|First Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]]\n|term_start2 = 18 September 1993\n|term_end2 = 20 January 1994\n|primeminister2 = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n|term_start3 = 2 March 1992\n|term_end3 = 15 December 1992\n|president3 = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|order4 = [[Ministry of Finance (Russia)|Minister of Finance]]\n|term_start4 = 11 November 1991\n|term_end4 = 2 April 1992\n|president4 = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|predecessor4 = Igor Lazarev\n|successor4 = Vasily Barchuk\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1956|3|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|12|16|1956|3|19|df=yes}}<ref name=rian>{{cite news|author=Anton Denisov|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20091216/157252785.html|title=Post-Soviet reform architect Gaidar dies aged 53 &#124; Top Russian news and analysis online &#124; 'RIA Novosti' newswire|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n|death_place = [[Odintsovo]], [[Russia]]\n|alma_mater = [[Lomonosov Moscow State University]]\n|spouse =Irina Smirnova <small>(div.)</small> <br>  Maria Strugatskaya\n|children = 3; including [[Maria Gaidar|Maria]]\n|religion =\n|party = [[Union of Rightist Forces]] {{small|(2001\u20132008)}}\n|otherparty = [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist]] {{small|(1980\u20131991)}}<br>[[Democratic Choice of Russia|Democratic Choice]] {{small|(1994\u20132001)}}\n|signature = Signature of Yegor Gaidar.png\n}}\n'''Yegor Timurovich Gaidar''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0415\u0433\u043e\u0301\u0440 \u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0440}}; {{IPA-ru|j\u026a\u02c8\u0261or t\u02b2\u026a\u02c8mur\u0259v\u02b2\u026at\u0255 \u0261\u0250j\u02c8dar|pron}}; 19 March 1956 \u2013 16 December 2009)<ref name=\"rian\" /> was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russians|Russian]] economist, politician, and author, and was the Acting [[Prime Minister of Russia]] from 15 June 1992 to 14 December 1992.\n\nHe was the architect of the controversial [[Shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]] reforms administered in Russia after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], which brought him both praise and harsh criticism. He participated in the preparation of the [[Belavezha Accords|Bialowieza agreements]]. Many Russians held him responsible for the economic hardships that plagued the country in the 1990s that resulted in mass poverty and [[hyperinflation]] among other things, although [[Liberalism in Russia|liberals]] praised him as a man who did what had to be done to save the country from complete collapse.<ref name=tel>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/6827912/Yegor-Gaidar.html Yegor Gaidar] [[The Daily Telegraph]]. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref> [[Jeffrey Sachs]], director of [[Columbia University]]'s [[The Earth Institute|Earth Institute]], who advised the Russian government in the early 1990s, called Gaidar \"the intellectual leader of many of Russia's political and economic reforms\" and \"one of the few pivotal actors\" of the period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601095&sid=aksFQ_yV.X00 |title=Yegor Gaidar, Shock Therapy Architect, Dies at 53 (Update2)|publisher=Bloomberg|date=30 May 2005|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nGaidar died of [[pulmonary edema]], provoked by [[Coronary artery disease|myocardial ischemia]]<ref name=\"iet.ru\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iet.ru/en/news-events/skonchalsya-e-t-gaidar.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228012553/http://www.iet.ru/en/news-events/skonchalsya-e-t-gaidar.html |archivedate=28 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> on 16 December 2009.\n\n==Personal life==\nGaidar was born in 1956 in [[Moscow]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|RSFSR]], [[Soviet Union]], the son of Ariadna Bazhova<ref name=\"bookref2\">{{Cite book|last=Ga\u012ddar|first=Egor Timurovich|title=Days of defeat and victory|publisher=University of Washington Press|year=1999|page=6|isbn=0-295-97823-6}}</ref> and ''[[Pravda]]'' military correspondent [[Timur Gaidar]], who fought in the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]] and was a friend of [[Ra\u00fal Castro]]. His paternal grandfather was Soviet writer [[Arkady Gaidar]] and his maternal grandfather was writer [[Pavel Bazhov]].<ref name=book1/> Gaidar married the daughter of writer [[Arkady Strugatsky]] during his time at the university.<ref name=book1>{{cite book|last=Medvedev|first=Roy Aleksandrovich|author2=George Shriver|title=Post-Soviet Russia: a journey through the Yeltsin era|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2000|page=[https://archive.org/details/postsovietrussia00medv/page/13 13]|isbn=0-231-10606-8|url=https://archive.org/details/postsovietrussia00medv/page/13}}</ref> His daughter, [[Maria Gaidar]], was one of the leaders of the Russian democratic opposition. From July 2009 till June 2011 she was Deputy Chair of the Government of [[Kirov oblast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ako.kirov.ru/power/government/bio/gaidar.php|title=\u0411\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438 \u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|language=ru|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930231128/http://www.ako.kirov.ru/power/government/bio/gaidar.php|archivedate=30 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=mt20715>[http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/news/article/525904.html Divisions Revealed as Kremlin Critic Moves to Work for Ukraine Government], [[The Moscow Times]] (20 July 2015)</ref> Since July 2015 she is a vice-governor of [[Odessa Oblast]] in [[Ukraine]].<ref name=mt20715/>\n\n==Career==\nGaidar graduated with honors from the [[Moscow State University]], [[MSU Faculty of Economics|Faculty of Economics]], in 1978 and worked as a researcher in several academic institutes. A long-time member of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] and an editor of the CPSU ideological journal ''Communist'' during the [[perestroika]], he joined [[Boris Yeltsin]]'s camp during [[Perestroika]]. In 1991 he quit the Communist Party{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} and was promoted to Yeltsin's government.\n\nWhile in government, Gaidar advocated [[free market]] economic reforms according to the principle of [[shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]]. His best-known decision was to abolish price regulation by the state, which immediately resulted in a major increase in prices and amounted to officially authorizing a [[market economy]] in Russia. He also cut military procurement and industrial subsidies, and reduced the budget deficit. Gaidar was the First Vice-Premier of the Russian Government and Minister of Economics from 1991 until 1992, and Minister of Finance from February 1992 until April 1992.\n\nHe was appointed Acting [[Prime Minister of Russia|Prime Minister]] under President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1992 from 15 June until 14 December, when the anti-Yeltsin Russian [[Congress of People's Deputies of Russia|Congress of People's Deputies]] refused to confirm Gaidar in this position and [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]] was eventually chosen as a compromise figure. Gaidar continued to advise the new government. On 18 September 1993, he was again appointed the First Vice-Premier under Chernomyrdin as a deliberate snub to the opposition. He played an active role in the [[1993 Russian constitutional crisis|Russian constitutional crisis of 1993]].\n\nOn 3 October, he famously spoke live on Russian television, then broadcasting from an emergency station near Moscow, as there was fighting going on in the Ostankino complex, calling on Muscovites to gather to defend Yeltsin's government so that Russia would not be \"turned into an enormous concentration camp for decades\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lqPLUz1Mlfg</ref>\n\nIn the [[1993 Russian legislative election|1993 Duma elections]], in the aftermath of the crisis, Gaidar led the pro-government bloc [[Democratic Choice of Russia|Russia's Choice]] and was seen by some as a possible future Prime Minister. However, due to the bloc's failure to win the plurality of votes in the election, Gaidar's role in the government diminished and he finally resigned on 20 January 1994.\n[[File:YegorGaidar.jpg|thumb|right|Gaidar in the early 1990s]]\nDuring the 1999 [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] Yegor Gaidar, [[Boris Nemtsov]] and [[Boris Fyodorov]] were in Belgrade, Yugoslavia on a mediation mission.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vor.ru/Kosovo/opinions_eng_29_03_99.html |title=Russia's Reaction to NATO Aggression Against Yugoslavia |date=29 March 1999 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archivedate=28 February 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050228164013/http://www.vor.ru/Kosovo/opinions_eng_29_03_99.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Reforms controversy===\nGaidar was often criticized for imposing ruthless reforms in 1992 with little care for their social impact; however, it has to be understood that the country back then was at the brink of a [[famine]]. Russia had no currency for buying import goods, at the same time, no-one gave credits as the country was essentially bankrupt.<ref>[http://expert.ru/2009/12/17/reformy_gaidara/ \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b] by \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432</ref> The collapse of the Soviet social system led to serious deterioration in [[standard of living|living standards]]. Millions of Russians were thrown into poverty due to their savings being devalued by massive [[hyperinflation]]. Moreover, the [[privatization in Russia|privatization]] and break-up of state assets left over from the Soviet Union, which he played a big part in, led to much of the country's wealth being handed to a small group of powerful business executives, later known as the [[Business oligarch#Yeltsinian oligarchs|Russian oligarchs]], for much less than what they were worth. The voucher privatization program enabled these few oligarchs to become billionaires specifically by arbitraging the vast difference between old domestic prices for Russian commodities and the prices prevailing on the world market. Because they stashed billions of dollars in Swiss bank accounts rather than investing in the Russian economy, these oligarchs were dubbed \"kleptocrats.\"<ref name=Granville>Johanna Granville, [https://www.academia.edu/5597850/The_Russian_Kleptocracy_and_Rise_of_Organized_Crime  \"''Dermokratizatsiya'' and ''Prikhvatizatsiya'': The Russian Kleptocracy and Rise of Organized Crime,\"]''Demokratizatsiya'' (summer 2003), pp. 448-457.</ref> As society grew to despise these figures and resent the economic and social turmoil caused by the reforms, Gaidar was often held by Russians as one of the men most responsible.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20091216/ts_nm/us_russia_gaidar_death |title=Russia's market reform architect Gaidar dies at 53|agency=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/Politics/2009-12-16/famous-russian-politician-yegor.html |title=Famous Russian politician Yegor Gaidar dies |work=[[Russia Today]] |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217114832/http://rt.com/Politics/2009-12-16/famous-russian-politician-yegor.html |archivedate=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> On the other hand, the ubiquitous goods deficit of the Soviet years disappeared and it became to be possible to buy all goods in the shops. Per capita calorie consumption under Gaidar diminished by 3.5% from 2526.88 kCal to 2438.17 kCal.<ref name=\"\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20091203153341/http://www.gks.ru/dbscripts/Cbsd/DBInet.cgi?pl=2340017 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442]</ref>\n\nAccording to Franklin Foer writing in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', however, \"when Yegor Gaidar ... asked the United States for help hunting down the billions that the KGB had carted away, the White House refused.\"<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/03/how-kleptocracy-came-to-america/580471</ref>\n\nOne of Gaidar's most outspoken critics was the [[Yabloko]] economist and MP [[Grigory Yavlinsky]], who had proposed since 1990 a [[500 Days]] programme for the transition of the whole USSR to market economic, which was first backed and then dismissed by the government of [[Nikolai Ryzhkov]]. Yavlinsky emphasized the differences between his and Gaidar's reforms program, such as the sequencing of [[privatization]] vs. [[Price controls|liberalization of prices]] and the applicability of his program to the entire Soviet Union.\n\nGaidar's supporters contend that although many mistakes were made, he had few choices in the matter and ultimately saved the country both from bankruptcy and from starvation. According to the [[BBC]]'s Andrei Ostalski, \"There were only two solutions\u2014either introduce [[Martial law in Russia|martial law]] and severe rationing, or radically liberalize the economy. The first option meant going all the way back to the [[stalinism|Stalinist]] system of mass repression. The second meant a colossal change, a journey\u2014or, rather, a race\u2014through uncharted waters with an unpredictable outcome.\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8416497.stm Yegor Gaidar: The price to pay] [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>\n\n==Death==\nGaidar died at the age of 53 in [[Odintsovo]] [[raion]], [[Moscow Oblast]], Russia.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8415441.stm|title=Yegor Gaidar, Russian economic reformer, dies aged 53|publisher=BBC News|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Gaidar's aide Valery Natarov stated that Gaidar died unexpectedly, early on 16 December 2009, at his Moscow Oblast home while he was working on a book<ref name=msnbc>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/34442309/ns/world_news-europe/ |title=Gaidar, Russia's free-market architect, dies at 53 - Business |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |date=17 October 2002 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy }}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} </ref> for children.\nGaidar died of [[pulmonary edema]], provoked by [[Coronary artery disease|myocardial ischemia]].<ref name=\"iet.ru\"/>\nHe is survived by his wife, three sons and daughter.<ref name=\"rian 2\">{{cite news|author=Anton Denisov|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20091216/157253141.html|title=Yegor Gaidar, architect of Russia's free market transition, dies &#124; Top Russian news and analysis online|agency=RIA Novosti|date=19 March 1956|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nFormer associates acknowledged Gaidar as an object of loathing among ordinary Russians who lost everything during the economic liberalization. However, many Russian citizens praised Gaidar as a man who averted greater catastrophes. \"He stood before the choice of civil war or painful reforms\", [[Boris Nemtsov]], a former deputy prime minister under Yeltsin, told the [[Echo of Moscow|Ekho Moskvy]] radio station. \"He gave his life to avert civil war.\"<ref name=msnbc/>\n\n[[Anatoly Chubais]], the minister responsible for privatization in the early 1990s, who considers himself a friend of Gaidar, praised Gaidar as Russia's \"savior\". \"It was Russia's huge good fortune that in one of the worst moments in its history it had Yegor Gaidar. In the early 1990s he saved the country from famine, civil war and disintegration\", Chubais wrote in his blog. \"Few people in the history of Russia and in world history can be compared with him for force of intellect, clarity of understanding of the past, present and future, and a willingness to take the most difficult but necessary decisions\", wrote Chubais.<ref name=\"rian 2\"/>\n\nFormer Deputy Minister of Fuel and Energy of Russia [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] and [[Platon Lebedev]] expressed their condolences.<ref>http://echo.msk.ru/news/641740-echo.html</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.svobodanews.ru/content/article/1905439.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0425\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439: \"\u041d\u0435\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f...\"|trans-title=Mikhail Khodorkovsky: \"Despite the differences ...\"|agency=Radio Fee Europe|date=16 December 2009}}</ref> \"He laid the foundation of our economy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://khodorkovsky.ru/documents/2009/12/16/13007/|title=\u041f\u0420\u0415\u0421\u0421\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u2013 \"\u041e\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u043e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043b\u0438\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0438 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c\"|publisher=Khodorkovsky.ru|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nRussian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] has expressed condolences to relatives and friends of Yegor Gaidar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kremlin.ru/news/6351|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=[[Kremlin.ru]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://echo.msk.ru/news/641735-echo.html|title=\u041f\u043e \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0443 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0430|trans-title=An investigation verification will be conducted  upon the death of a prominent politician and economist Yegor Gaidar|publisher=Echo.msk.ru|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Medvedev called Gaidar a \"daring, honest and decisive\" economist who \"evoked respect among his supporters and opponents.\"<ref name=usatoday1>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2009-12-16-russia-gaidar-obit_N.htm?csp=34|title=Gaidar, acting Russian PM under Yeltsin, dies|work=[[USA Today]]|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Gaidar was a brave, honest, and determined man, who \"assumed responsibility for unpopular but essential measures in a period of radical change,\" the president said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/politics/russian/remembering-russias-yegor-gaidar/?fullstory |title=Remembering Russia's \"shock doctor\" Yegor Gaidar |agency=RT |accessdate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy }}{{dead link|date=March 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n[[File:Gravestone Y.Gaidar.jpg|thumb|Sculptural composition on Yegor Gaidar's grave. Moskow, Novodevichy Cemetery. Sculptor \u0410.V. Balashov.]]\n\"The death of Gaidar is a heavy loss for Russia,\" says Russian Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rian.ru/society/20091216/199566915.html|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u2013 \u0442\u044f\u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f \u0443\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438, \u0441\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d|trans-title=Gaidar's death - heavy loss for Russia, Putin said|agency=RIA Novosti|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> \"We have lost a genuine citizen and patriot, a strong spirited person, a talented scientist, writer and expert.... He didn't dodge responsibility and 'took the punch' in the most challenging situations with honor and courage,\" the statement said.<ref name=usatoday1/>\n\nThe [[White House]] offered condolences over Gaidar's death. Although controversial, Gaidar's legacy formed the foundation of a dynamic market-based economy and is destined to live on, [[United States National Security Council|U.S. National Security Council]] spokesman [[Michael A. Hammer|Mike Hammer]] said. Hammer described him as a top-notch intellectual, a true Russian patriot and a leading brain behind Russia\u2019s political and economic reforms in the past two decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2009/12/17/3063155.html |title=White House offers condolences over Gaidar's death |agency=[[Voice of Russia]] |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archivedate=16 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716085329/http://english.ruvr.ru/2009/12/17/3063155.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Gaidar Forum===\nIn honor of Yegor Gaidar, each year in mid-January the Russian Presidency holds a conference that attracts the Russian political and business elite, with top European politicians also attending. The 2014 Forum was hosted by [[Dmitry Medvedev]], with presentations by former Czech President [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], former Italian Prime Minister [[Mario Monti]], and former Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister [[Simeon Djankov]]. The [[Gaidar Forum]] is organized the week before [[Davos]] and thus also serves to formulate the Russian positions on a variety of topics.\n\n==Academic and political positions==\n\n===Positions held===\n*Director of the [[Institute for Economy in Transition]]<ref>[http://www.iep.ru/ ''Gaidar Institute for Economic Policy'']</ref>\n*Executive Vice-President of the [[International Democrat Union|International Democratic Union]] (Conservative International)\n*Steering Committee member \"Arrabida Meetings\" (Portugal)\n*Member of the Baltic Sea Cooperation Council under the Prime-Minister of Sweden\n*Member of the Editorial Board of \"Vestnik Evropy\" (Moscow)\n*Member of the Advisory Board of the \"Acta Oeconomica\" (Budapest)\n*Member of the Advisory Board of the CASE Foundation (Warsaw)\n*Member of the International Advisory Board of the Moscow School of Management SKOLKOVO<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.SKOLKOVO.ru|title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041a\u041e\u041b\u041a\u041e\u0412\u041e \u2013 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041a\u041e\u041b\u041a\u041e\u0412\u041e|publisher=Skolkovo.ru|date=16 December 2007|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> (Moscow)\n\n===Honorary positions===\n*Honorary Professor, [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n*Terry Sanford Distinguished Lecturer, [[Duke University]]\n*Honorary Academy member of the Ukrainian Academy of Management\n*Honorary Director, Russia-Ukraine Institute for Personnel and Management\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Collapse of an Empire: Lessons for Modern Russia'', by Yegor Gaidar, Brookings Institution Press (17 October 2007), {{ISBN|0-8157-3114-0}}.\n*''Russian Reform / International Money'' (Lionel Robbins Lectures) by Yegor Gaidar and Karl Otto P\u00f6hl (Hardcover \u2013 6 July 1995)\n*''Days of Defeat and Victory'' (Jackson School Publications in International Studies) by E. T. Gaidar, Yegor Gaidar, Michael McFaul, and Jane Ann Miller (Dec 1999)\n*''State and Evolution: Russia's Search for a Free Market'' by E. T. Gaidar, Yegor Gaidar, and Jane Ann Miller (Donald R. Ellegood International Publications) Hardcover (Aug 2003) {{ISBN|978-0295983493}}\n*''The Economics of Russian Transition'' by Yegor Gaidar (15 August 2002)\n*''Ten Years of Russian Economic Reform'' by Sergei Vasiliev and Yegor Gaidar (25 March 1999)\n*''Russia: A Long View'', by Yegor Gaidar (Author), Antonina W. Bouis (Translator), Anders Aslund (Foreword), The MIT Press (October 12, 2012), {{ISBN|0-2620-1741-5}}.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Leszek Balcerowicz]] - architect of the shock therapy reforms in Poland.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gaidar.org/ Yegor Gaidar's home page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090420223725/http://www.aei.org/publications/pubID.25991/pub_detail.asp Speech], explaining the underlying reasons for the dissolution of the Soviet Union\n*[https://archive.today/20130415220647/http://www.theconnection.org/2000/01/26/yegor-gaidar-and-russian-economic-reform Interview] in 2000 with Boston radio\n*[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/34442309/ns/world_news-europe/ Gaidar, acting Russian PM under Yeltsin, dies]{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/6827912/Yegor-Gaidar.html Yegor Gaidar] \u2013 Daily Telegraph obituary\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box\n|title = [[Prime Minister of Russia]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n|years = 15 June 1992 \u2013 14 December 1992\n|before = [[Boris Yeltsin]]<br />{{small|(Acting)}}\n|after = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Russia}}\n{{Finance ministers of Russia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaidar, Yegor}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Acting Prime Ministers of the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:Duke University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the State Duma (Russian Federation)]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Soviet economists]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Russian economists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from edema]]\n[[Category:Burials at Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Union of Right Forces politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Choice of Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:Russian liberals]]\n[[Category:Russian Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|\u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440, \u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Timurovich|Gaidar}}\n\n{{Infobox prime minister\n|birth_name=Yegor Timurovich Gaidar\n|name = Yegor Gaidar<br />{{small|\u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440}}\n|image = Gaidar in 2008 - crop.jpg\n|imagesize = 240px\n|caption = Gaidar in 2008\n|office = [[Prime Minister of Russia]]<br>{{small|Acting}}\n|term_start = 15 June 1992\n|term_end = 15 December 1992\n|1blankname = [[First Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation|First Deputy]]\n|1namedata = [[Vladimir Shumeyko]]\n|president = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|predecessor = [[Boris Yeltsin]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|successor = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n|order2 = [[First Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation|First Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]]\n|term_start2 = 18 September 1993\n|term_end2 = 20 January 1994\n|primeminister2 = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n|term_start3 = 2 March 1992\n|term_end3 = 15 December 1992\n|president3 = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|order4 = [[Ministry of Finance (Russia)|Minister of Finance]]\n|term_start4 = 11 November 1991\n|term_end4 = 2 April 1992\n|president4 = [[Boris Yeltsin]]\n|predecessor4 = Igor Lazarev\n|successor4 = Vasily Barchuk\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1956|3|19|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]], [[Soviet Union]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|12|16|1956|3|19|df=yes}}<ref name=rian>{{cite news|author=Anton Denisov|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20091216/157252785.html|title=Post-Soviet reform architect Gaidar dies aged 53 &#124; Top Russian news and analysis online &#124; 'RIA Novosti' newswire|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n|death_place = [[Odintsovo]], [[Russia]]\n|alma_mater = [[Lomonosov Moscow State University]]\n|spouse =Irina Smirnova <small>(div.)</small> <br>  Maria Strugatskaya\n|children = 3; including [[Maria Gaidar|Maria]]\n|religion =\n|party = [[Union of Rightist Forces]] {{small|(2001\u20132008)}}\n|otherparty = [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist]] {{small|(1980\u20131991)}}<br>[[Democratic Choice of Russia|Democratic Choice]] {{small|(1994\u20132001)}}\n|signature = Signature of Yegor Gaidar.png\n}}\n'''Yegor Timurovich Gaidar''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0415\u0433\u043e\u0301\u0440 \u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0440}}; {{IPA-ru|j\u026a\u02c8\u0261or t\u02b2\u026a\u02c8mur\u0259v\u02b2\u026at\u0255 \u0261\u0250j\u02c8dar|pron}}; 19 March 1956 \u2013 16 December 2009)<ref name=\"rian\" /> was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and [[Russians|Russian]] economist, politician, and author, and was the Acting [[Prime Minister of Russia]] from 15 June 1992 to 14 December 1992.\n\nHe was the architect of the controversial [[Shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]] reforms administered in Russia after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], which brought him both praise and harsh criticism. He participated in the preparation of the [[Belavezha Accords|Bialowieza agreements]]. Many Russians held him responsible for the economic hardships that plagued the country in the 1990s that resulted in mass poverty and [[hyperinflation]] among other things, although [[Liberalism in Russia|liberals]] praised him as a man who did what had to be done to save the country from complete collapse.<ref name=tel>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/6827912/Yegor-Gaidar.html Yegor Gaidar] [[The Daily Telegraph]]. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref> [[Jeffrey Sachs]], director of [[Columbia University]]'s [[The Earth Institute|Earth Institute]], who advised the Russian government in the early 1990s, called Gaidar \"the intellectual leader of many of Russia's political and economic reforms\" and \"one of the few pivotal actors\" of the period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601095&sid=aksFQ_yV.X00 |title=Yegor Gaidar, Shock Therapy Architect, Dies at 53 (Update2)|publisher=Bloomberg|date=30 May 2005|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nGaidar died of [[pulmonary edema]], provoked by [[Coronary artery disease|myocardial ischemia]]<ref name=\"iet.ru\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iet.ru/en/news-events/skonchalsya-e-t-gaidar.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228012553/http://www.iet.ru/en/news-events/skonchalsya-e-t-gaidar.html |archivedate=28 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> on 16 December 2009.\n\n==Personal life==\nGaidar was born in 1956 in [[Moscow]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|RSFSR]], [[Soviet Union]], the son of Ariadna Bazhova<ref name=\"bookref2\">{{Cite book|last=Ga\u012ddar|first=Egor Timurovich|title=Days of defeat and victory|publisher=University of Washington Press|year=1999|page=6|isbn=0-295-97823-6}}</ref> and ''[[Pravda]]'' military correspondent [[Timur Gaidar]], who fought in the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]] and was a friend of [[Ra\u00fal Castro]]. His paternal grandfather was Soviet writer [[Arkady Gaidar]] and his maternal grandfather was writer [[Pavel Bazhov]].<ref name=book1/> Gaidar married the daughter of writer [[Arkady Strugatsky]] during his time at the university.<ref name=book1>{{cite book|last=Medvedev|first=Roy Aleksandrovich|author2=George Shriver|title=Post-Soviet Russia: a journey through the Yeltsin era|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2000|page=[https://archive.org/details/postsovietrussia00medv/page/13 13]|isbn=0-231-10606-8|url=https://archive.org/details/postsovietrussia00medv/page/13}}</ref> His daughter, [[Maria Gaidar]], was one of the leaders of the Russian democratic opposition. From July 2009 till June 2011 she was Deputy Chair of the Government of [[Kirov oblast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ako.kirov.ru/power/government/bio/gaidar.php|title=\u0411\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438 \u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|language=ru|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930231128/http://www.ako.kirov.ru/power/government/bio/gaidar.php|archivedate=30 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=mt20715>[http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mobile/news/article/525904.html Divisions Revealed as Kremlin Critic Moves to Work for Ukraine Government], [[The Moscow Times]] (20 July 2015)</ref> Since July 2015 she is a vice-governor of [[Odessa Oblast]] in [[Ukraine]].<ref name=mt20715/>\n\n==Career==\nGaidar graduated with honors from the [[Moscow State University]], [[MSU Faculty of Economics|Faculty of Economics]], in 1978 and worked as a researcher in several academic institutes. A long-time member of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] and an editor of the CPSU ideological journal ''Communist'' during the [[perestroika]], he joined [[Boris Yeltsin]]'s camp during [[Perestroika]]. In 1991 he quit the Communist Party{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} and was promoted to Yeltsin's government.\n\nWhile in government, Gaidar advocated [[free market]] economic reforms according to the principle of [[shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]]. His best-known decision was to abolish price regulation by the state, which immediately resulted in a major increase in prices and amounted to officially authorizing a [[market economy]] in Russia. He also cut military procurement and industrial subsidies, and reduced the budget deficit. Gaidar was the First Vice-Premier of the Russian Government and Minister of Economics from 1991 until 1992, and Minister of Finance from February 1992 until April 1992.\n\nHe was appointed Acting [[Prime Minister of Russia|Prime Minister]] under President [[Boris Yeltsin]] in 1992 from 15 June until 14 December, when the anti-Yeltsin Russian [[Congress of People's Deputies of Russia|Congress of People's Deputies]] refused to confirm Gaidar in this position and [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]] was eventually chosen as a compromise figure. Gaidar continued to advise the new government. On 18 September 1993, he was again appointed the First Vice-Premier under Chernomyrdin as a deliberate snub to the opposition. He played an active role in the [[1993 Russian constitutional crisis|Russian constitutional crisis of 1993]].\n\nOn 3 October, he famously spoke live on Russian television, then broadcasting from an emergency station near Moscow, as there was fighting going on in the Ostankino complex, calling on Muscovites to gather to defend Yeltsin's government so that Russia would not be \"turned into an enormous concentration camp for decades\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lqPLUz1Mlfg</ref>\n\nIn the [[1993 Russian legislative election|1993 Duma elections]], in the aftermath of the crisis, Gaidar led the pro-government bloc [[Democratic Choice of Russia|Russia's Choice]] and was seen by some as a possible future Prime Minister. However, due to the bloc's failure to win the plurality of votes in the election, Gaidar's role in the government diminished and he finally resigned on 20 January 1994.\n[[File:YegorGaidar.jpg|thumb|right|Gaidar in the early 1990s]]\nDuring the 1999 [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] Yegor Gaidar, [[Boris Nemtsov]] and [[Boris Fyodorov]] were in Belgrade, Yugoslavia on a mediation mission.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vor.ru/Kosovo/opinions_eng_29_03_99.html |title=Russia's Reaction to NATO Aggression Against Yugoslavia |date=29 March 1999 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archivedate=28 February 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050228164013/http://www.vor.ru/Kosovo/opinions_eng_29_03_99.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Reforms controversy===\nGaidar was often criticized for imposing ruthless reforms in 1992 with little care for their social impact; however, it has to be understood that the country back then was at the brink of a [[famine]]. Russia had no currency for buying import goods, at the same time, no-one gave credits as the country was essentially bankrupt.<ref>[http://expert.ru/2009/12/17/reformy_gaidara/ \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b] by \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432</ref> The collapse of the Soviet social system led to serious deterioration in [[standard of living|living standards]]. Millions of Russians were thrown into poverty due to their savings being devalued by massive [[hyperinflation]]. Moreover, the [[privatization in Russia|privatization]] and break-up of state assets left over from the Soviet Union, which he played a big part in, led to much of the country's wealth being handed to a small group of powerful business executives, later known as the [[Business oligarch#Yeltsinian oligarchs|Russian oligarchs]], for much less than what they were worth. The voucher privatization program enabled these few oligarchs to become billionaires specifically by arbitraging the vast difference between old domestic prices for Russian commodities and the prices prevailing on the world market. Because they stashed billions of dollars in Swiss bank accounts rather than investing in the Russian economy, these oligarchs were dubbed \"kleptocrats.\"<ref name=Granville>Johanna Granville, [https://www.academia.edu/5597850/The_Russian_Kleptocracy_and_Rise_of_Organized_Crime  \"''Dermokratizatsiya'' and ''Prikhvatizatsiya'': The Russian Kleptocracy and Rise of Organized Crime,\"]''Demokratizatsiya'' (summer 2003), pp. 448-457.</ref> As society grew to despise these figures and resent the economic and social turmoil caused by the reforms, Gaidar was often held by Russians as one of the men most responsible.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20091216/ts_nm/us_russia_gaidar_death |title=Russia's market reform architect Gaidar dies at 53|agency=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/Politics/2009-12-16/famous-russian-politician-yegor.html |title=Famous Russian politician Yegor Gaidar dies |work=[[Russia Today]] |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217114832/http://rt.com/Politics/2009-12-16/famous-russian-politician-yegor.html |archivedate=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> On the other hand, the ubiquitous goods deficit of the Soviet years disappeared and it became to be possible to buy all goods in the shops. Per capita calorie consumption under Gaidar diminished by 3.5% from 2526.88 kCal to 2438.17 kCal.<ref name=\"\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20091203153341/http://www.gks.ru/dbscripts/Cbsd/DBInet.cgi?pl=2340017 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442]</ref>\n\nAccording to Franklin Foer writing in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', however, \"when Yegor Gaidar ... asked the United States for help hunting down the billions that the KGB had carted away, the White House refused.\"<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/03/how-kleptocracy-came-to-america/580471</ref>\n\nOne of Gaidar's most outspoken critics was the [[Yabloko]] economist and MP [[Grigory Yavlinsky]], who had proposed since 1990 a [[500 Days]] programme for the transition of the whole USSR to market economic, which was first backed and then dismissed by the government of [[Nikolai Ryzhkov]]. Yavlinsky emphasized the differences between his and Gaidar's reforms program, such as the sequencing of [[privatization]] vs. [[Price controls|liberalization of prices]] and the applicability of his program to the entire Soviet Union.\n\nGaidar's supporters contend that although many mistakes were made, he had few choices in the matter and ultimately saved the country both from bankruptcy and from starvation. According to the [[BBC]]'s Andrei Ostalski, \"There were only two solutions\u2014either introduce [[Martial law in Russia|martial law]] and severe rationing, or radically liberalize the economy. The first option meant going all the way back to the [[stalinism|Stalinist]] system of mass repression. The second meant a colossal change, a journey\u2014or, rather, a race\u2014through uncharted waters with an unpredictable outcome.\"<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8416497.stm Yegor Gaidar: The price to pay] [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>\n\n==Death==\nGaidar died at the age of 53 in [[Odintsovo]] [[raion]], [[Moscow Oblast]], Russia.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8415441.stm|title=Yegor Gaidar, Russian economic reformer, dies aged 53|publisher=BBC News|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Gaidar's aide Valery Natarov stated that Gaidar died unexpectedly, early on 16 December 2009, at his Moscow Oblast home while he was working on a book<ref name=msnbc>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/34442309/ns/world_news-europe/ |title=Gaidar, Russia's free-market architect, dies at 53 - Business |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |date=17 October 2002 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy }}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} </ref> for children.\nGaidar died of [[pulmonary edema]], provoked by [[Coronary artery disease|myocardial ischemia]].<ref name=\"iet.ru\"/>\nHe is survived by his wife, three sons and daughter.<ref name=\"rian 2\">{{cite news|author=Anton Denisov|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20091216/157253141.html|title=Yegor Gaidar, architect of Russia's free market transition, dies &#124; Top Russian news and analysis online|agency=RIA Novosti|date=19 March 1956|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nFormer associates acknowledged Gaidar as an object of loathing among ordinary Russians who lost everything during the economic liberalization. However, many Russian citizens praised Gaidar as a man who averted greater catastrophes. \"He stood before the choice of civil war or painful reforms\", [[Boris Nemtsov]], a former deputy prime minister under Yeltsin, told the [[Echo of Moscow|Ekho Moskvy]] radio station. \"He gave his life to avert civil war.\"<ref name=msnbc/>\n\n[[Anatoly Chubais]], the minister responsible for privatization in the early 1990s, who considers himself a friend of Gaidar, praised Gaidar as Russia's \"savior\". \"It was Russia's huge good fortune that in one of the worst moments in its history it had Yegor Gaidar. In the early 1990s he saved the country from famine, civil war and disintegration\", Chubais wrote in his blog. \"Few people in the history of Russia and in world history can be compared with him for force of intellect, clarity of understanding of the past, present and future, and a willingness to take the most difficult but necessary decisions\", wrote Chubais.<ref name=\"rian 2\"/>\n\nFormer Deputy Minister of Fuel and Energy of Russia [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] and [[Platon Lebedev]] expressed their condolences.<ref>http://echo.msk.ru/news/641740-echo.html</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.svobodanews.ru/content/article/1905439.html|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0425\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439: \"\u041d\u0435\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u044f...\"|trans-title=Mikhail Khodorkovsky: \"Despite the differences ...\"|agency=Radio Fee Europe|date=16 December 2009}}</ref> \"He laid the foundation of our economy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://khodorkovsky.ru/documents/2009/12/16/13007/|title=\u041f\u0420\u0415\u0421\u0421\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0425\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438 \u041f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u2013 \"\u041e\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u043e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043b\u0438\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0438 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043c\"|publisher=Khodorkovsky.ru|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nRussian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] has expressed condolences to relatives and friends of Yegor Gaidar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kremlin.ru/news/6351|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=[[Kremlin.ru]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://echo.msk.ru/news/641735-echo.html|title=\u041f\u043e \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0443 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0415\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0430|trans-title=An investigation verification will be conducted  upon the death of a prominent politician and economist Yegor Gaidar|publisher=Echo.msk.ru|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Medvedev called Gaidar a \"daring, honest and decisive\" economist who \"evoked respect among his supporters and opponents.\"<ref name=usatoday1>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2009-12-16-russia-gaidar-obit_N.htm?csp=34|title=Gaidar, acting Russian PM under Yeltsin, dies|work=[[USA Today]]|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> Gaidar was a brave, honest, and determined man, who \"assumed responsibility for unpopular but essential measures in a period of radical change,\" the president said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/politics/russian/remembering-russias-yegor-gaidar/?fullstory |title=Remembering Russia's \"shock doctor\" Yegor Gaidar |agency=RT |accessdate=17 December 2009 |df=dmy }}{{dead link|date=March 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n[[File:Gravestone Y.Gaidar.jpg|thumb|Sculptural composition on Yegor Gaidar's grave. Moskow, Novodevichy Cemetery. Sculptor \u0410.V. Balashov.]]\n\"The death of Gaidar is a heavy loss for Russia,\" says Russian Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rian.ru/society/20091216/199566915.html|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u2013 \u0442\u044f\u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f \u0443\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438, \u0441\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d|trans-title=Gaidar's death - heavy loss for Russia, Putin said|agency=RIA Novosti|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> \"We have lost a genuine citizen and patriot, a strong spirited person, a talented scientist, writer and expert.... He didn't dodge responsibility and 'took the punch' in the most challenging situations with honor and courage,\" the statement said.<ref name=usatoday1/>\n\nThe [[White House]] offered condolences over Gaidar's death. Although controversial, Gaidar's legacy formed the foundation of a dynamic market-based economy and is destined to live on, [[United States National Security Council|U.S. National Security Council]] spokesman [[Michael A. Hammer|Mike Hammer]] said. Hammer described him as a top-notch intellectual, a true Russian patriot and a leading brain behind Russia\u2019s political and economic reforms in the past two decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2009/12/17/3063155.html |title=White House offers condolences over Gaidar's death |agency=[[Voice of Russia]] |date=17 December 2009 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |archivedate=16 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716085329/http://english.ruvr.ru/2009/12/17/3063155.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Gaidar Forum===\nIn honor of Yegor Gaidar, each year in mid-January the Russian Presidency holds a conference that attracts the Russian political and business elite, with top European politicians also attending. The 2014 Forum was hosted by [[Dmitry Medvedev]], with presentations by former Czech President [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], former Italian Prime Minister [[Mario Monti]], and former Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister [[Simeon Djankov]]. The [[Gaidar Forum]] is organized the week before [[Davos]] and thus also serves to formulate the Russian positions on a variety of topics.\n\n==Academic and political positions==\n\n===Positions held===\n*Director of the [[Institute for Economy in Transition]]<ref>[http://www.iep.ru/ ''Gaidar Institute for Economic Policy'']</ref>\n*Executive Vice-President of the [[International Democrat Union|International Democratic Union]] (Conservative International)\n*Steering Committee member \"Arrabida Meetings\" (Portugal)\n*Member of the Baltic Sea Cooperation Council under the Prime-Minister of Sweden\n*Member of the Editorial Board of \"Vestnik Evropy\" (Moscow)\n*Member of the Advisory Board of the \"Acta Oeconomica\" (Budapest)\n*Member of the Advisory Board of the CASE Foundation (Warsaw)\n*Member of the International Advisory Board of the Moscow School of Management SKOLKOVO<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.SKOLKOVO.ru|title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041a\u041e\u041b\u041a\u041e\u0412\u041e \u2013 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041a\u041e\u041b\u041a\u041e\u0412\u041e|publisher=Skolkovo.ru|date=16 December 2007|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> (Moscow)\n\n===Honorary positions===\n*Honorary Professor, [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n*Terry Sanford Distinguished Lecturer, [[Duke University]]\n*Honorary Academy member of the Ukrainian Academy of Management\n*Honorary Director, Russia-Ukraine Institute for Personnel and Management\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Collapse of an Empire: Lessons for Modern Russia'', by Yegor Gaidar, Brookings Institution Press (17 October 2007), {{ISBN|0-8157-3114-0}}.\n*''Russian Reform / International Money'' (Lionel Robbins Lectures) by Yegor Gaidar and Karl Otto P\u00f6hl (Hardcover \u2013 6 July 1995)\n*''Days of Defeat and Victory'' (Jackson School Publications in International Studies) by E. T. Gaidar, Yegor Gaidar, Michael McFaul, and Jane Ann Miller (Dec 1999)\n*''State and Evolution: Russia's Search for a Free Market'' by E. T. Gaidar, Yegor Gaidar, and Jane Ann Miller (Donald R. Ellegood International Publications) Hardcover (Aug 2003) {{ISBN|978-0295983493}}\n*''The Economics of Russian Transition'' by Yegor Gaidar (15 August 2002)\n*''Ten Years of Russian Economic Reform'' by Sergei Vasiliev and Yegor Gaidar (25 March 1999)\n*''Russia: A Long View'', by Yegor Gaidar (Author), Antonina W. Bouis (Translator), Anders Aslund (Foreword), The MIT Press (October 12, 2012), {{ISBN|0-2620-1741-5}}.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Leszek Balcerowicz]] - architect of the shock therapy reforms in Poland.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gaidar.org/ Yegor Gaidar's home page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090420223725/http://www.aei.org/publications/pubID.25991/pub_detail.asp Speech], explaining the underlying reasons for the dissolution of the Soviet Union\n*[https://archive.today/20130415220647/http://www.theconnection.org/2000/01/26/yegor-gaidar-and-russian-economic-reform Interview] in 2000 with Boston radio\n*[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/34442309/ns/world_news-europe/ Gaidar, acting Russian PM under Yeltsin, dies]{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/6827912/Yegor-Gaidar.html Yegor Gaidar] \u2013 Daily Telegraph obituary\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box\n|title = [[Prime Minister of Russia]]<br />{{small|Acting}}\n|years = 15 June 1992 \u2013 14 December 1992\n|before = [[Boris Yeltsin]]<br />{{small|(Acting)}}\n|after = [[Viktor Chernomyrdin]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Russia}}\n{{Finance ministers of Russia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaidar, Yegor}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Acting Prime Ministers of the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:Duke University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the State Duma (Russian Federation)]]\n[[Category:Moscow State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Soviet economists]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Russian economists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from edema]]\n[[Category:Burials at Novodevichy Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Union of Right Forces politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Choice of Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:Russian liberals]]\n[[Category:Russian Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Shouwa Genroku", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yegor_Gaidar"}
{"title_page": "List of contemporary art galleries", "text_new": "{{short description|List of contemporary art galleries}}\nThis is a list of [[contemporary art]] galleries, i.e., commercial galleries for-profit, privately owned businesses dealing in artworks by contemporary artists born after [[1945]].\n\nGalleries on this list meet the following criteria:\n*The gallery has played a major role in career of significant or well-known artists born after 1945\n*The gallery has won significant critical attention\n*The gallery is widely cited by his/her peers or successors\n\n==List of contemporary art galleries==\n===Intercontinental===\n* [[Gavin Brown's Enterprise]], New York since 1994, Roma since 2015\n* Galerie Ceysson & B\u00e9n\u00e9ti\u00e8re ([[Fran\u00e7ois Ceysson]] et [[Lo\u00efc B\u00e9n\u00e9ti\u00e8re]]), Saint-Etienne since 2006, Luxembourg since 2008, Paris since 2009, Geneva since 2012, New York since 2017\n* Galleria Continua, ([[Mario Cristiani]], [[Lorenzo Fiaschi]] et [[Maurizio Rigillo]]), San Gimignano since 1990, Beijing since 2005, Les Moulins since 2007, La Havana since 2015, Roma since 2020\n* Galleria [[Massimo De Carlo]], Milan since 1987, London since 2009, Hong Kong since 2016\n* [[Gagosian Gallery]], Los Angeles since 1979, New York since 1989, London since 2000, Roma since 2007, Athena since 2009, Paris and Geneva since 2010, Hong Kong since 2011, Le Bourget since 2012, San Francisco since 2016, Basel since 2019\n* [[Barbara Gladstone]] Gallery, New York since 1979, Brussels since 2011\n* [[Marian Goodman]] Gallery, New York since 1977, Paris since 1999, London since 2014\n* [[Hauser & Wirth]], ([[Iwan Wirth]] et [[Manuela Hauser]]), Zurich since 1992, London since 2003, New York since 2009, Somerset since 2014, Los Angeles since 2016, Hong Kong since 2018, Gstaad since 2019\n* [[Yvon Lambert Gallery]], Paris from 1966 to 2014, New York from 2003 to 2014\n* [[Simon Lee Gallery]], London since 2002, Hong Kong since 2012, New York since 2014\n* Galerie [[Daniel Lelong]], Paris and Zurich since 1981, New York since 1985\n* [[Lisson Gallery]], ([[Nicholas Logsdail]]), London since 1967, New York since 2016, Shanghai since 2019\n* [[Pace Gallery]] ([[Arme Glimcher]] et [[Marc Glimcher]]), New York since 1963, London since 2012, Hong Kong since 2014, Palo Alto since 2016, Seoul since 2017, Geneva since 2018\n* Galerie [[Emmanuel Perrotin]], Paris since 1990, Hong Kong since 2012, New York since 2013, Seoul since 2016, Tokyo since 2017, Shanghai since 2018\n* Galerie [[Almine Rech]], Paris since 1997, Brussels since 2007, London since 2014, New York since 2016, Shanghai since 2019\n* [[Spr\u00fcth Magers]] ([[Monika Spr\u00fcth]] et [[Philomene Magers]]), Cologne since 1983, London since 2003, Berlin since 2008, Los Angeles since 2016\n* [[David Zwirner Gallery]], New York since 1993, London since 2012, Hong Kong since 2017, Paris since 2019\n* [[Galerie Michael Werner]], Berlin (1963-1969), Cologne (1969-1990), New York since 1990, Trebbin since 2009, London since 2012\n* [[White Cube]], ([[Jay Jopling]]), London since 1993, Hong Kong since 2012\n\n=== America ===\n==== United States of America ====\n===== Transmetropolitan =====\n* [[Marianne Boesky Gallery]], New York since 1996, Aspen since 2017\n* [[Richard Gray]] Gallery, Chicago since 1963, New York since 1997\n* [[Maccarone (art gallery)|Michele Maccarone]] Gallery, New York since 2001, Los Angeles since 2015\n* [[Team Gallery]], (Jos\u00e9 Freire and Lisa Ruyter), New York since 1996, Los Angeles since 2014\n\n===== Chicago =====\n* [[Kavi Gupta]] Gallery, since 2000\n\n===== Los Angeles =====\n* [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]], since 1978\n* [[L.A. Louver]] Gallery, since 1976\n* [[Regen Projects]] (Stuart Regen and Shaun Caley), since 1989\n\n===== New York =====\n* [[Mary Boone]] Gallery, from 1977 to 2019\n* [[Leo Castelli]] Gallery (dead in 1999), since 1957\n* [[Paula Cooper Gallery]], since 1968\n* D'Amelio Gallery ([[Christopher D'Amelio]]), since 1996\n* Eden Fine Art, ([[Cathia Klimovsky]]) since 1997\n* [[Luhring Augustine Gallery]], ([[Lawrence Luhring]] et [[Roland Augustine]]), since 1998\n* [[Metro Pictures Gallery]], ([[Janelle Reiring]] et [[Helene Winer]]), since 1980\n* Nahmad Contemporary Gallery, ([[Joe Nahmad (New York)|Joe Nahmad]]), since 2013\n* [[Annina Nosei]] Gallery, from 1980 to 2006\n* [[Jack Shainman Gallery]], since 1984\n* [[Ileana Sonnabend|Sonnabend Gallery]] (dead in 2007), since 1970\n* [[Reena Spaulings]] Fine Art, since 2005\n* [[Sperone Westwater]], ([[Gian Enzo Sperone]] et [[Angela Westwater]]), since 1975\n* [[Friederich Petzel]] Gallery, since 1994\n\n===== Saint Louis =====\n* [[David Bruno]] Gallery, New York (1983-2005) then Saint Louis since 2005\n\n===== San Francisco =====\n* Gallery [[Paule Anglim]], since 1972\n\n===== Seattle =====\n* [[Greg Kucera]] Gallery, since 1983\n\n=== Europe ===\n==== European ====\n* [[Thomas Dane]] Gallery, London since 2004, Naples since 2018\n* [[Galerie Max Hetzler]], Stuttgart (1974-1983), Cologne (1983-1993), Berlin since 1993, Paris since 2014, London since 2018\n* [[Galerie Kamel Mennour]], Paris since 1999, London since 2016\n* Galerie Monitor, ([[Paola Capata]]), Rome depuis 2003, Lisbon since 2017, Pereto since 2019\n* [[Victoria Miro Gallery]], London since 1985, Venice since 2017\n* Galerie [[Nathalie Obadia]], Paris since 1993, Brussels since 2008\n* [[Galerie Thaddaeus Ropac]], Salzburg since 1983, Paris since 1990, Pantin since 2012, London since 2017\n* Galerie [[Daniel Templon]], Paris since 1966, Brussels since 2013\n* Galerie [[Michel Rein]], Tours from 1992 to 2000, Paris since 2000, Brussels since 2013\n* [[Tornabuoni Art]], ([[Roberto Casamonti]]), Florence since 1981, Crans Montana since 1993, Milan since 1995, Forte Dei Marmi since 2004, Paris since 2009, London since 2015\n\n=== Asia ===\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Art world}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of contemporary art galleries}}\n[[Category:Types of art museums and galleries]]\n[[Category:Business of visual arts]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art galleries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|List of contemporary art galleries}}\nThis is a list of [[contemporary art]] galleries, i.e., commercial galleries for-profit, privately owned businesses dealing in artworks by contemporary artists born after [[1945]].\n\nGalleries on this list meet the following criteria:\n*The gallery has played a major role in career of significant or well-known artists born after 1945\n*The gallery has won significant critical attention\n*The gallery is widely cited by his/her peers or successors\n\n==List of contemporary art galleries==\n===Intercontinental===\n* [[Gavin Brown's Enterprise]], New York since 1994, Roma since 2015\n* Galerie Ceysson & B\u00e9n\u00e9ti\u00e8re ([[Fran\u00e7ois Ceysson]] et [[Lo\u00efc B\u00e9n\u00e9ti\u00e8re]]), Saint-Etienne since 2006, Luxembourg since 2008, Paris since 2009, Geneva since 2012, New York since 2017\n* Galleria Continua, ([[Mario Cristiani]], [[Lorenzo Fiaschi]] et [[Maurizio Rigillo]]), San Gimignano since 1990, Beijing since 2005, Les Moulins since 2007, La Havana since 2015, Roma since 2020\n* Galleria [[Massimo De Carlo]], Milan since 1987, London since 2009, Hong Kong since 2016\n* [[Gagosian Gallery]], Los Angeles since 1979, New York since 1989, London since 2000, Roma since 2007, Athena since 2009, Paris and Geneva since 2010, Hong Kong since 2011, Le Bourget since 2012, San Francisco since 2016, Basel since 2019\n* [[Barbara Gladstone]] Gallery, New York since 1979, Brussels since 2011\n* [[Marian Goodman]] Gallery, New York since 1977, Paris since 1999, London since 2014\n* [[Hauser & Wirth]], ([[Iwan Wirth]] et [[Manuela Hauser]]), Zurich since 1992, London since 2003, New York since 2009, Somerset since 2014, Los Angeles since 2016, Hong Kong since 2018, Gstaad since 2019\n* [[Yvon Lambert Gallery]], Paris from 1966 to 2014, New York from 2003 to 2014\n* [[Simon Lee Gallery]], London since 2002, Hong Kong since 2012, New York since 2014\n* Galerie [[Daniel Lelong]], Paris and Zurich since 1981, New York since 1985\n* [[Lisson Gallery]], ([[Nicholas Logsdail]]), London since 1967, New York since 2016, Shanghai since 2019\n* [[Pace Gallery]] ([[Arme Glimcher]] et [[Marc Glimcher]]), New York since 1963, London since 2012, Hong Kong since 2014, Palo Alto since 2016, Seoul since 2017, Geneva since 2018\n* Galerie [[Emmanuel Perrotin]], Paris since 1990, Hong Kong since 2012, New York since 2013, Seoul since 2016, Tokyo since 2017, Shanghai since 2018\n* Galerie [[Almine Rech]], Paris since 1997, Brussels since 2007, London since 2014, New York since 2016, Shanghai since 2019\n* [[Spr\u00fcth Magers]] ([[Monika Spr\u00fcth]] et [[Philomene Magers]]), Cologne since 1983, London since 2003, Berlin since 2008, Los Angeles since 2016\n* [[David Zwirner Gallery]], New York since 1993, London since 2012, Hong Kong since 2017, Paris since 2019\n* [[Galerie Michael Werner]], Berlin (1963-1969), Cologne (1969-1990), New York since 1990, Trebbin since 2009, London since 2012\n* [[White Cube]], ([[Jay Jopling]]), London since 1993, Hong Kong since 2012\n\n=== America ===\n==== United States of America ====\n===== Transmetropolitan =====\n* [[Marianne Boesky Gallery]], New York since 1996, Aspen since 2017\n* [[Richard Gray]] Gallery, Chicago since 1963, New York since 1997\n* [[Maccarone (art gallery)|Michele Maccarone]] Gallery, New York since 2001, Los Angeles since 2015\n* [[Team Gallery]], (Jos\u00e9 Freire and Lisa Ruyter), New York since 1996, Los Angeles since 2014\n\n===== Chicago =====\n* [[Kavi Gupta]] Gallery, since 2000\n\n===== Los Angeles =====\n* [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]], since 1978\n* [[L.A. Louver]] Gallery, since 1976\n* [[Regen Projects]] (Stuart Regen and Shaun Caley), since 1989\n\n===== New York =====\n* [[Mary Boone]] Gallery, New York from 1977 to 2019\n* [[Leo Castelli]] Gallery (dead in 1999), since 1957\n* [[Paula Cooper Gallery]], since 1968\n* D'Amelio Gallery ([[Christopher D'Amelio]]), since 1996\n* Eden Fine Art, ([[Cathia Klimovsky]]) since 1997\n* [[Luhring Augustine Gallery]], ([[Lawrence Luhring]] et [[Roland Augustine]]), since 1998\n* [[Metro Pictures Gallery]], ([[Janelle Reiring]] et [[Helene Winer]]), since 1980\n* Nahmad Contemporary Gallery, ([[Joe Nahmad (New York)|Joe Nahmad]]), since 2013\n* [[Annina Nosei]] Gallery, from 1980 to 2006\n* [[Jack Shainman Gallery]], since 1984\n* [[Ileana Sonnabend|Sonnabend Gallery]] (dead in 2007), since 1970\n* [[Reena Spaulings]] Fine Art, since 2005\n* [[Sperone Westwater]], ([[Gian Enzo Sperone]] et [[Angela Westwater]]), since 1975\n* [[Friederich Petzel]] Gallery, since 1994\n\n===== Saint Louis =====\n* [[David Bruno]] Gallery, New York (1983-2005) then Saint Louis since 2005\n\n===== San Francisco =====\n* Gallery [[Paule Anglim]], since 1972\n\n===== Seattle =====\n* [[Greg Kucera]] Gallery, since 1983\n\n=== Europe ===\n==== European ====\n* [[Thomas Dane]] Gallery, London since 2004, Naples since 2018\n* [[Galerie Max Hetzler]], Stuttgart (1974-1983), Cologne (1983-1993), Berlin since 1993, Paris since 2014, London since 2018\n* [[Galerie Kamel Mennour]], Paris since 1999, London since 2016\n* Galerie Monitor, ([[Paola Capata]]), Rome depuis 2003, Lisbon since 2017, Pereto since 2019\n* [[Victoria Miro Gallery]], London since 1985, Venice since 2017\n* Galerie [[Nathalie Obadia]], Paris since 1993, Brussels since 2008\n* [[Galerie Thaddaeus Ropac]], Salzburg since 1983, Paris since 1990, Pantin since 2012, London since 2017\n* Galerie [[Daniel Templon]], Paris since 1966, Brussels since 2013\n* Galerie [[Michel Rein]], Tours from 1992 to 2000, Paris since 2000, Brussels since 2013\n* [[Tornabuoni Art]], ([[Roberto Casamonti]]), Florence since 1981, Crans Montana since 1993, Milan since 1995, Forte Dei Marmi since 2004, Paris since 2009, London since 2015\n\n=== Asia ===\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Art worl