{"title_page": "Araruama Futebol Clube", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Araruama\n| image = <!-- Resolu\u00e7\u00e3o da imagem, o padr\u00e3o \u00e9 120px -->\n| fullname = Araruama Futebol Clube\n| nickname =\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|2016|2|6}}\n| ground = [[Corre\u00e3o]],<br>[[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| capacity = 12,000\n| chairman = \u00c1lvaro Michele Conte Fernando Captain Mor Vithor Nametala\n| manager = Thiago Jardim\n| league = [[Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2|S\u00e9rie B2]]\n| season = 2019\n| position = \n| website = https://araruamafc.com.br/ (in Portuguese)\n| pattern_la1 = _araruama18h\n| pattern_b1 = _araruama18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _araruama18h\n| leftarm1 = 0000ff\n| body1 = 0000ff\n| rightarm1 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = 0000ff\n| pattern_la2 = _araruama18a\n| pattern_b2 =_araruama18a\n| pattern_ra2 = _araruama18a\n| leftarm2 = ffffff\n| body2 = ffffff\n| rightarm2 = ffffff\n| shorts2 = ffffff\n| socks2 = ffffff\n|\n}}\n'''Araruama Futebol Clube''', better known as '''Araruama''', is a [[football]] club in the city of [[Araruama]], [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rj/serra-lagos-norte/noticia/2016/06/araruama-ganha-clube-com-cunho-social-que-vai-jogar-serie-c-do-rio.html |title=Araruama ganha Clube com cunho social que vai jogar a S\u00e9rie C do Rio |author= G1 |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref> The team currently plays in the [[Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2|S\u00e9rie B2]].\n\n==History==\nConceived and founded on June 2, 2016 by three medical friends from the city of Araruama who played football for fun, came the idea of creating a professional club after the departure of the last professional club in the city. In order to occupy this gap left in the city, the three friends came together and developed the project, joining a professional club Arraial do Cabo (CEAC) with Araruama Futebol Clube. \nThe elaboration of a team made up of local players is a recipe for success. For years, championship after championship, the city attracted fans who continued to support and make a healthy movement, a cause of joy and leisure for city dwellers. The AFC comes to supply this absence and add its existence in the history of the city's sport. At times the stories of football and the city of Araruama mix. \nIn the 1960s, the mayor of the city of the time was a defender of a professional team (article published by the newspaper O GLOBO). The city has already had the honor of having as player Sinval, athlete who played for the Brazilian national team, who died in 2012, in which a tribute was paid to the player in one of the games of the state of that year. \nAraruama F.C. competes in the Campeonato Carioca Profissional de S\u00e9rie B2 of professionals and in the category of juniors.  \n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.araruamafc.com.br/ Club Site]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Brazilian football clubs]]\n\n\n{{Football in Rio de Janeiro}}\n{{Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Rio de Janeiro (state)| Araruama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Araruama\n| image = <!-- Resolu\u00e7\u00e3o da imagem, o padr\u00e3o \u00e9 120px -->\n| fullname = Araruama Futebol Clube\n| nickname =\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|2016|2|6}}\n| ground = [[Corre\u00e3o]],<br>[[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| capacity = 12,000\n| chairman = \u00c1lvaro Michele Conte Fernando Captain Mor Vithor Nametala\n| manager = Thiago Jardim\n| league = [[Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2|S\u00e9rie B2]]\n| season = 2019\n| position = \n| website = https://araruamafc.com.br/ (in Portuguese)\n| pattern_la1 = _araruama18h\n| pattern_b1 = _araruama18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _araruama18h\n| leftarm1 = 0000ff\n| body1 = 0000ff\n| rightarm1 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = 0000ff\n| pattern_la2 = _araruama18a\n| pattern_b2 =_araruama18a\n| pattern_ra2 = _araruama18a\n| leftarm2 = ffffff\n| body2 = ffffff\n| rightarm2 = ffffff\n| shorts2 = ffffff\n| socks2 = ffffff\n|\n}}\n'''Araruama Futebol Clube''', better known as '''Araruama''', is a club in the city of [[Araruama]], [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/rj/serra-lagos-norte/noticia/2016/06/araruama-ganha-clube-com-cunho-social-que-vai-jogar-serie-c-do-rio.html |title=Araruama ganha Clube com cunho social que vai jogar a S\u00e9rie C do Rio |author= G1 |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>The team currently plays in the [[Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2|S\u00e9rie B2]].\n\n==History==\nConceived and founded on June 2, 2016 by three medical friends from the city of Araruama who played football for fun, came the idea of creating a professional club after the departure of the last professional club in the city. In order to occupy this gap left in the city, the three friends came together and developed the project, joining a professional club Arraial do Cabo (CEAC) with Araruama Futebol Clube. \nThe elaboration of a team made up of local players is a recipe for success. For years, championship after championship, the city attracted fans who continued to support and make a healthy movement, a cause of joy and leisure for city dwellers. The AFC comes to supply this absence and add its existence in the history of the city's sport. At times the stories of football and the city of Araruama mix. \nIn the 1960s, the mayor of the city of the time was a defender of a professional team (article published by the newspaper O GLOBO). The city has already had the honor of having as player Sinval, athlete who played for the Brazilian national team, who died in 2012, in which a tribute was paid to the player in one of the games of the state of that year. \nAraruama F.C. competes in the Campeonato Carioca Profissional de S\u00e9rie B2 of professionals and in the category of juniors.  \n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.araruamafc.com.br/ Club Site]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Brazilian football clubs]]\n\n\n{{Football in Rio de Janeiro}}\n{{Campeonato Carioca S\u00e9rie B2}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Rio de Janeiro (state)| Araruama]]\n", "name_user": "Doomsdayer520", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Araruama_Futebol_Clube"}
{"title_page": "Prelude in F-sharp minor (Rachmaninoff)", "text_new": "[[Image:Prelude Op. 23.1, Rachmaninoff.png|thumb|375px|right|The rising and falling melodic pattern in the opening.]]\n\nThe '''Prelude in F-sharp minor, Op. 23, No. 1''' is a composition by [[Sergei Rachmaninoff]] completed and premiered in 1903.<ref>Norris, Geoffrey, ''Rachmaninoff'', Schirmer Books, 1993 (pg. 170).</ref><ref>''Id.''</ref> It is one of  [[Rachmaninoff op. 23|ten preludes]] composed by Rachmaninoff in 1901 and 1903.\n\n== Structure ==\nThe prelude is [[ternary form|ternary]] in nature. The \"A\" section (measures 1\u201313) introduces the first theme, section \"B\" (13\u201330) introduces a new set of variations, and measures 30\u201341 mark an altered return to the original \"A\" theme. Each of the larger ternary sections contains its set of \"micro-variations\" marked by changes in note values, dynamics, and rhythm. For instance, the \"A\" theme, introduced in measures 1 and 2, is varied in measure 8.\n\n[[Image:Rachmaninoff op.23 no 1 m 2.jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 2<br />\n<br />\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 8.jpg|300px]]<br />\n<br />\nMeasure 8\n\nThe Prelude proceeds from [[F-sharp minor]] to the relative major ([[A major]]) in measure 13, and returns to the [[tonic (music)|tonic]] in measure 30.\n\nA \"hidden\" [[chromatic]] sequence in the \"A\" section occurs in the bass line on the second beat of measure 1 and the first beat of measures 2\u20136. This sequence is later revealed as the basis for the \"B\" theme, first introduced transitorily as a modulation between the \"A\" and \"B\" sections. Compare measures 6 and 24: \n\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 6 .jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 6<br />\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 24.jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 24\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Rachmaninoff solo piano}}\n\n[[Category:Preludes by Sergei Rachmaninoff]]\n[[Category:Compositions in F-sharp minor]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Prelude Op. 23.1, Rachmaninoff.png|thumb|375px|right|The rising and falling melodic pattern in the opening.]]\n\nThe '''Prelude in F-sharp minor, Op. 23, No. 1''' is a composition by [[Sergei Rachmaninoff]] completed and premiered in 1903.<ref>Norris, Geoffrey, ''Rachmaninoff'', Schirmer Books, 1993 (pg. 170).</ref><ref>''Id.''</ref> It is one of  [[Rachmaninoff op. 23|ten preludes]] composed by Rachmaninoff in 1901 and 1903.\n\n== Structure ==\nThe prelude is [[ternary form|ternary]] and [[homophonic]] in nature. The \"A\" section (measures 1\u201313) introduces the first theme, section \"B\" (13\u201330) introduces a new set of variations, and measures 30\u201341 mark an altered return to the original \"A\" theme. Each of the larger ternary sections contains its set of \"micro-variations\" marked by changes in note values, dynamics, and rhythm. For instance, the \"A\" theme, introduced in measures 1 and 2, is varied in measure 8.\n\n[[Image:Rachmaninoff op.23 no 1 m 2.jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 2<br />\n<br />\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 8.jpg|300px]]<br />\n<br />\nMeasure 8\n\nThe Prelude proceeds from [[F-sharp minor]] to the relative major ([[A major]]) in measure 13, and returns to the [[tonic (music)|tonic]] in measure 30.\n\nA \"hidden\" [[chromatic]] sequence in the \"A\" section occurs in the bass line on the second beat of measure 1 and the first beat of measures 2\u20136. This sequence is later revealed as the basis for the \"B\" theme, first introduced transitorily as a modulation between the \"A\" and \"B\" sections. Compare measures 6 and 24: \n\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 6 .jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 6<br />\n[[File:Rachmaninoff op 23 No. 1 m 24.jpg|300px]]<br />\nMeasure 24\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Rachmaninoff solo piano}}\n\n[[Category:Preludes by Sergei Rachmaninoff]]\n[[Category:Compositions in F-sharp minor]]\n", "name_user": "Thelanternwholaughs42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Innappropriate wording.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prelude_in_F-sharp_minor_(Rachmaninoff)"}
{"title_page": "Fatima Akilu", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian psychologist and a public speaker}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fatima Akilu \n| image         =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Fatima Akilu, at the Trust Women Conference, in London, Britain Dec. 1, 2016.\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Nigerian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Psychologist]], CVE Expert, Executive Director Neem Foundation\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =  Counselled [[John Hinckley Jr]], Pioneered Nigeria's CVE Programme\n}}\n\n'''Fatima Akilu''' is a Nigerian psychologist and a public speaker in the areas of Preventing and Countering Violent Extremism (CVE) and Counter-Terrorism.<ref name=\"tonyblairfaithfoundation.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://tonyblairfaithfoundation.org/sites/default/files/How%20to%20Prevent_Global%20Perspectives%20Vol%202_0.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-01-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521132555/http://tonyblairfaithfoundation.org/sites/default/files/How%20to%20Prevent_Global%20Perspectives%20Vol%202_0.pdf |archive-date=2017-05-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> She is currently the Executive Director of Neem Foundation,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.neemfoundation.org.ng/staff-profiles/Dr-Fatima-Akilu|title=Dr. Fatima Akilu {{!}} neem|last=|first=|date=|website=Neemfoundation.org.ng|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> and the former Director of Behavioural Analysis and Strategic Communication at the Office of the National Security Adviser in Nigeria, where she worked on the country's Countering Violent Extremism Programme in 2014.<ref name=\"tonyblairfaithfoundation.org\"/> She also is a part of The Global Strategy Network team with  industry expert [[Richard Barrett (counter-terrorism expert)|Richard Barrett]] and other individuals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobalstrategynetwork.org/team/|title=WHO WE ARE|website=Theglobalstrategynetwork.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118224209/https://www.theglobalstrategynetwork.org/team/|archive-date=2017-01-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFatima is also a children's book writer, and a partner of the Women's Alliance for Security Leadership (WASL).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://podbay.fm/show/1117542794/e/1467223200?autostart=1|title=Voice of a Practitioner in Nigeria \u2013 Fatima Akilu from On Violent Extremism|website=Podbay.fm|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to Ali Akilu (late Secretary of the defunct Northern region) and Hajia Astajam, Dr. Akilu was educated at the [[Beechwood Sacred Heart School]], [[Royal Tunbridge Wells|Tunbridge Wells]]. She holds a Ph.D. and MRes in Psychology from [[University of Reading|Reading University]], United Kingdom and a B.A. in English and Psychology from [[Mount St. Mary's University (Los Angeles)]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201101140331.html|title=Nigeria: Akilu, Waziri-Ibrahim, Araceli Join Leadership|last=|first=|date=14 Jan 2011|website=AllAfrica|access-date=26 Dec 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Akilu|first=Fatima|title=A multimethod investigation into the experience of single homelessness.|date=1994|degree=Ph.D.|publisher=University of Reading|url=https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do;jsessionid=87230C1A08AC9BD5DDCFE3AA35AAED71?uin=uk.bl.ethos.307003}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFatima Akilu is a [[NHS England|NHS]] trained forensic psychologist who specializes in the treatment of offenders with developmental and psychiatric disorders, she has over 20 years experience in the field of mental health and psychology. As a youth worker in London, Fatima counselled homeless young people, and while working at a psychiatric hospital in Washington she counselled [[John Hinckley Jr.|John Hinckley Jr]], the man who attempted to assassinate [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/nigeria/11644162/Meet-the-former-NHS-psychologist-trying-to-get-inside-the-mind-of-Boko-Haram.html|title=Meet the former NHS psychologist trying to get inside the mind of Boko Haram|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\nShe is also a university educator and an advocate for marginalized groups, working in the area of psychology and health for more than two decades.<ref name=\"concordconsulting.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://concordconsulting.org/fatima-akilu-2 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119050311/http://concordconsulting.org/fatima-akilu-2/ |archive-date=2017-01-19 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Working as an Adjunct Professor of General Psychology at [[SUNY Broome Community College]] (USA) for over 12 years, she has taught and authored several research papers relating to homelessness, ethnicity and their relationship with mental health.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wildsmith|first=E.|last2=Akilu|first2=F.|last3=Sashidharan|first3=S. P.|last4=Cochrane|first4=R.|last5=Commander|first5=M. J.|date=1999-10-01|title=Mental health care for Asian, black and white patients with non-affective psychoses: pathways to the psychiatric hospital, in-patient and after-care|journal=Social Psychiatry and Psychiatric Epidemiology|language=en|volume=34|issue=9|pages=484\u2013491|doi=10.1007/s001270050224|issn=1433-9285}}</ref>\n\nPreviously Head of Communication for the Senior Special Assistant to the President on the Millennium Development Goals, she was Chairman of the Editorial Board Leadership Newspapers.<ref name=\"concordconsulting.org\"/> Akilu was former Director of Behavioral Analysis and Strategic Communication at the Office of the [[National Security Advisor (Nigeria)|National Security Advisor in Nigeria]], where she worked on the country's Countering Violent Extremism Programme between 2012 and 2015.<ref name=\"tonyblairfaithfoundation.org\"/> The CVE programme is part of the government's long-term strategy to tackle [[Boko Haram]]; the terror group responsible for the deaths of over 20,000 people across Nigeria.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/nigeria/11915708/Fears-for-Nigerias-counter-radicalisation-programme-as-British-trained-head-is-ousted.html|title=Fears for Nigeria's counter-radicalisation programme as British-trained head is ousted|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>  Described as a sophisticated and research-based attempt to understand and address the causes and effects of the insurgency, Nigeria's CVE Programme is a multi-disciplinary intervention targeting ex Boko Haram members, youth, and other vulnerable groups through social programmes that provide them with positive alternatives to violent extremism. These programmes focused on the nexus between development and security at the community level.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Akilu has worked with liberated wives of Boko Haram commanders, who pose a unique challenge since they often experienced respected and privileged positions within the insurgency society and often long to return.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/dispatch/the-women-rescued-from-boko-haram-who-are-returning-to-their-captors|title=The Women Rescued from Boko Haram Who Are Returning to Their Captors|last=Nwaobani|first=Adaobi Tricia|date=20 Dec 2018|website=New Yorker|access-date=26 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\nAkilu is currently the Executive Director of Neem Foundation, a [[Non-governmental organization|Non-Governmental Organisation]] founded as a direct response to the problem of insecurity in Nigeria.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Writing==\nAkilu is also a children's book writer, who has authored over 17 children's books. She has authored a series of eight books on the Millennium Development Goals for children to teach children about multiculturalism as well as worldwide development issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pubmatch.com/profile/5176/fatima-akilu.html|title=Fatima Akilu - Nigeria Book Author: Contact Details, Books, Biography|website=PubMatch|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>  She currently leads a campaign to have Nigerian children read 100 books a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/nigeria/11644162/Meet-the-former-NHS-psychologist-trying-to-get-inside-the-mind-of-Boko-Haram.html|title=Meet the former NHS psychologist trying to get inside the mind of Boko Haram|last=Freeman|first=Colin|date=2015-06-02|access-date=2017-10-20|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Published work==\n* ''Ngozi Comes to Town'' ([[Cassava Republic Press]], 2008)\n* ''Timi's Dream Comes True'' (Cassava Republic Press, 2008)\n* ''Ketwa Plays the Drum'' (Cassava Republic Press, 2011)\n* ''Yinka Washes His Hand'' (Cassava Republic Press)\n* ''The Red Transistor Radio'' (Cassava Republic Press)\n* ''The Yellow Mosquito Net'' (Cassava Republic Press)\n* ''Preye and the Sea of Plastic'' (Cassava Republic Press)\n* ''Aliyah Learns a New Dance'' (Cassava Republic Press)\n* ''Zahra and Coco Alphabet'' (Mockingbird Publishers)\n* ''Ashraf: Flying Saucer'' (Mockingbird Publishers, 2011)\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* Zahra and Coco Alphabet, 2012 Winner of Moonbeam Children's Book Award's Gold prize in the Alphabet/ Counting Book category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moonbeamawards.com/47/winners/2012-winners|title=2012 Winners|website=Moonbeamawards.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n* \u2018Preye and the Sea of Plastics\u2019 by Fatima Akilu and \u2018Mayowa and the Masquerade\u2019 by [[Lola Shoneyin]]: Joint Winners for the ANA/Atiku Abubakar Prize for Children's Literature.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akilu, Fatima}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nigerian psychologists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian psychologist and a public speaker}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Fatima Akilu \n| image         =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Fatima Akilu, at the Trust Women Conference, in London, Britain Dec. 1, 2016.\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Nigerian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Psychologist]], CVE Expert, Executive Director Neem Foundation\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =  Counselled [[John Hinckley Jr]], Pioneered Nigeria's CVE Programme\n}}\n\n'''Fatima Akilu''' is a Nigerian psychologist and a public speaker in the areas of Preventing and Countering Violent Extremism (CVE) and Counter-Terrorism.<ref name=\"tonyblairfaithfoundation.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://tonyblairfaithfoundation.org/sites/default/files/How%20to%20Prevent_Global%20Perspectives%20Vol%202_0.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-01-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521132555/http://tonyblairfaithfoundation.org/sites/default/files/How%20to%20Prevent_Global%20Perspectives%20Vol%202_0.pdf |archive-date=2017-05-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> She is currently the Executive Director of Neem Foundation,<ref name=\"